        <bioghist id="ref3">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Edward Falkowski (1901-1984), was a journalist and writer, trade unionist, and radical, who was politically close to the communist movement in the 1920s--1940s. He was born in Shenandoah, Pennslyvania, and as a teenager, began working in the coal mines, and became active in the United Mine Workers. In 1926, Falkowski began attending Brookwood Labor College in Katonah, New York, on a UMW scholarship. During this time, his articles and poetry first appeared in 
                <emph render="italic">Labor Age</emph> and 
                <emph render="italic">New Masses</emph>. In 1928, he traveled to Germany as a work exchange student. Encouraged by friends and attracted politically to the Russian Revolution, he decided to visit and write about the Soviet Union, arriving in May, 1930, and remained for seven years, during which time he worked as a journalist for the 
                <emph render="italic">Moscow News</emph> (an English language paper), married, and began raising a family. In 1937, he left the Soviet Union and returned to the United States, where he settled in Toledo, Ohio, taught for a time at Commonwealth College in Mena, Arkansas, was drafted into the army, remarried, and continued his writing activities. In the mid 1940s, at the urging of Lew Krzycki, he helped organize, and worked for the Communist-associated American Slav Congress. Later he directed a Polish press agency. As a factory worker at Emerson Electric Company in the 1950s, Falkowski was active in his union, UAW Local 365 in Queens, New York, and eventually moved into a management position.</p>
        </bioghist>
