        <scopecontent id="ref1">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>The collection contains published and unpublished writings, correspondence, journals, scrapbooks, and a variety of labor union records, which are arranged in six series: Series I, Correspondence is primarily with his family (wife and siblings). Prominent correspondents include Joseph North, Jack Conroy, Louis Adamic, Elizabeth Gurely Flynn. Series II, contains the journals he maintained throughout his life which are particularly valuable for their documentation of Falkowski's early years, and his time in Germany and the Soviet Union. Series III, Literary Manuscripts, has been divided by genre: poetry, sketches, short stories, plays, novels. Four unique issues of a literary journal produced by Falkowski and friends in Pennsylvania in 1924 25 attest to the cultural vitality of a mining community. Falkowski used two pseudonyms: "Edward Fulsky" in the 1920s and "Polonicus" in the 1970s. Series IV, Published Works are arranged chronologically. Many of the early articles are extremely brittle. Journals for which Falkowski wrote include: 
                <emph render="italic">Labor Age</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">New Masses</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">Rebel Poet</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">The Anvil</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">Moscow News</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">Polish American Journal</emph>, 
                <emph render="italic">People's Voice</emph>, and 
                <emph render="italic">Federated Press</emph>, a left labor news service. Series V, contains twenty-seven scrapbooks, given sixteen subject titles by Falkowski. The major areas are mine workers and the UMW, Polish Americans, and Americans in the USSR. Series VI, Union Activity, covers his years during the 1950s at Eagle Electric.</p>
